# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2024-chicago-white-sox-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1902 Chicago White Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Sox had a record of 74–60, finishing in fourth place in the American League.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 season was the seventh season overall for the Chicago White Sox, and their sixth season in the major leagues.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won their second American League pennant and their first World Series championship.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The Sox won 93 games in the regular season–– a plateau they would not reach again until the 1915 season–– to claim the pennant, propelled by a historic 19-game winning streak in August.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] They won the league pennant largely on the strength of their pitching staff, as their team batting average of .230 was the worst in the AL.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The 1906 White Sox team became known as the *Hitless Wonders*, having won the American League pennant despite posting the lowest team batting average (.230) in the league.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team had been in fourth place by the end of July, 7½ games behind the defending champion Philadelphia Athletics, when they went on a 19-game winning streak that drove them into first place.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] No American League team would beat the 19-game winning streak for almost 100 years.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The team made up for their lack of hitting prowess by leading the league in walks, hit batsmen and sacrifice hits.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox pitching staff had a league-leading 32 shutouts and the second lowest earned run average in the league.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/1906-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox then defeated their cross-town rivals, the heavily favored Chicago Cubs in the 1906 World Series.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The **2024 Chicago White Sox season** was the club's 125th season in Chicago, their 124th in the American League and their 34th at Rate Field.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] It was their first full season under general manager Chris Getz.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] This record was also the second worst in modern baseball history, behind only the 1988 Orioles' 0–21 and 2–23 start.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] On June 6, following a defeat to the Boston Red Sox, the White Sox established a franchise record for the most consecutive losses at 14.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] During this losing streak, the White Sox had their first winless homestand of at least seven games in franchise history, going 0–7.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] On July 14, following a defeat to the Pittsburgh Pirates, the White Sox established a new MLB record for the highest number of losses before the All-Star break, totaling 71.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The record was broken the following year by the Colorado Rockies, who lost 74 games.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The franchise record for consecutive losses was broken again on July 29 when the White Sox dropped their 15th straight game.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The streak continued, and on August 5, the White Sox lost their 21st consecutive game.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] This marked the first time since the 1988 Baltimore Orioles that a team endured a 21-game losing streak.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] They managed to end the streak the following day with a victory over the Athletics.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox became the first team since the 2021 Baltimore Orioles to go through two separate losing streaks of 14 games or more.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Furthermore, they set a record for the fastest assurance of a losing season by losing 82 of their first 109 games, surpassing the 2003 Detroit Tigers, who lost 82 of their first 111 games.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] On August 8, the White Sox dismissed manager Pedro Grifol after the team fell to 28–89, finishing his managing career at 89–190.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] On that same day, the team appointed Grady Sizemore as the interim manager.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] On August 17, with their loss to the Houston Astros, the White Sox became the first team to be eliminated from playoff contention in 2024.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] This surpassed the 2018 Baltimore Orioles for the earliest clinch of missing the playoffs since the divisional era began in 1969.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Eight days later, on August 25, the White Sox became the fastest team since the 1916 Philadelphia Athletics to lose 100 games in a season when they lost to their division rival Detroit Tigers, dropping them to 31–100.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The team set a new franchise record for losses when they lost their 107th game of the season on September 1 to the New York Mets.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] With this loss, the White Sox had their first 0–10 homestand in franchise history and became the first team since the 1965 Mets to have three losing streaks of at least ten games.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The 0–10 homestand was part of a franchise record 16 straight home losses.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] It was also part of a 12-game losing streak.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] After their 118th loss to the San Diego Padres on September 20, the 2024 White Sox would join the 2003 Tigers as the only American League teams to lose at least 118 games.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] That loss also ensured the White Sox would lose at least once against all 29 of the other MLB teams in one season, making them the first team in MLB history to suffer this fate.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] On September 27, the White Sox lost their 121st game of the season to the Detroit Tigers, surpassing the 1962 New York Mets for the most losses in modern MLB history.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] However, the White Sox later finished the season at 41–121 (.253), three tenths of a percentage point better than the 1962 Mets.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] September proved to be their best month of the season as they went 10–15 and also had a record of 5–1 in their last 6 games, with their only loss coming from the aforementioned Tigers game.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] On September 22, the White Sox lost 4–2 to the San Diego Padres, earning their 120th loss.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] This surpassed the American League record set by the 2003 Detroit Tigers and tied the Major League record set by the 1962 expansion New York Mets.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Following the game, several sports and news outlets ran articles discussing the potential for the White Sox to lose one of their remaining six games of the season to the Los Angeles Angels at home or the Tigers in Detroit to break the modern single-season loss record.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] As a result, many White Sox fans bought tickets to home games against the Angels, hoping to witness the historic game where the team surpassed the modern loss record.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Mixes of cheers and boos came from White Sox fans during the games when their team executed well, while fans yelled phrases such as "Sell the team!" when the team made mistakes.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox won all three home games against the Angels to keep their record at 120 losses, resulting in fans throughout the stadium booing the White Sox.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] White Sox outfielder Andrew Benintendi acknowledged the fans' reaction after the game by saying: "People here tonight were trying to see history.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] They're going to have to wait one more day.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] During the games, White Sox fans held signs mentioning the historical significance of the potential loss, including one sign bearing "121" in the font of the White Sox logo.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox swept the Angels, winning their final home game of the season with a 7–0 score, resulting in a standing ovation from most of the White Sox fans in the stadium.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Prior to facing the Tigers, Interim manager Grady Sizemore stated that despite the frustration surrounding their exceptional win-loss record, the White Sox players were ultimately professionals who would not be shaken by it, and trusted that they would play to compete and to win.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] He further stated that since the Tigers were attempting to clinch a playoff spot, the White Sox wanted to do their best to spoil it.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The September 27 game remained scoreless through the first four innings, with both teams' starting pitchers performing effectively.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The Tigers' broke the deadlock in the bottom of the 5th inning, with Jake Rogers scoring from third base on a wild pitch thrown by Jared Shuster.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Matt Vierling hit a sacrifice fly two pitches later, scoring Parker Meadows to put Detroit up 2–0.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The White Sox responded in the top of the 6th inning, with Zach DeLoach hitting a home run to right field, the first of his major league career, to cut the lead to 2–1.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] The Tigers extended their lead in the bottom of the 7th, when Andy Ibáñez led off with a double to right-center and reached third base due to a fielding error by center fielder Dominic Fletcher.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Riley Greene hit a 412-foot double to score Ibáñez.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Later in the inning, another wild pitch thrown by Fraser Ellard scored Vierling, pushing Detroit's lead to 4–1.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Detroit relied entirely on their bullpen for pitching, with multiple relievers combining to effectively limit the White Sox to a single run.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] After Brenan Hanifee started the game, rookie Brant Hurter was credited with the win after pitching four innings, while back end relievers Tyler Holton, Will Vest, and Jason Foley pitched the late innings, with Foley picking up his 28th save of the season.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Sizemore stated that the season was "not the year we wanted" following the game, and expressed that while he began to grow frustrated well before the team was close to the loss record he stated that he was not sure if he would feel different if he had lost only 115 or 110 games instead.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Pitcher Garrett Crochet remarked on the record: "Obviously it sucks." and that "We put ourselves in this position early on.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] We are where we are because of the way we played.
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Note: No league ERA qualifiers (162 innings pitched, 1 inning pitched per scheduled game).
[src:2024-chicago-white-sox-season/2024-chicago-white-sox-season] Pitcher Garrett Crochet won MLB Pitcher of the Month for June after he went 1–1 in six starts with an ERA of 1.91 along with a 0.93 WHIP in 37+2⁄3 innings while striking out 56 batters.
